* ============================================================
*  PINOCCHIO NAV DEFECT PROOF -- CDX/LMDB endpoint + skip timing
*
*  Status:  CANDIDATE / REVIEW_BEFORE_EXECUTION. Read-only (no mutation).
*  Purpose: Prove the TOP/BOTTOM/GO/GOTO/SKIP navigation fix on the big
*           64-bit (DBF_64) CDX/LMDB tables.
*
*  WHAT WAS WRONG (before the fix)
*  -------------------------------
*  TOP/BOTTOM and ordered SKIP on a CDX order fell through the CNX code
*  path: they scanned every DBF record, built 6.5M keys, sorted them, and
*  built two large caches just to return ONE record. On ENROLL (5.5M rows)
*  that is why TOP was "super slow" -- minutes, and hundreds of MB of RAM.
*
*  WHAT THE FIX DOES
*  -----------------
*  CDX is now separated from CNX and routed through the IndexManager backend
*  cursor -- the same path GO TOP/GOTO already used -- which resolves the LMDB
*  env via SET PATH LMDB (env lives at LMDB/<...>/<table>.cdx.d, NOT next to
*  the .cdx container). TOP/BOTTOM stream that cursor and stop at the first
*  record: one index op, independent of table size. Ordered SKIP builds its
*  position cache from the ascending index cursor instead of scanning + sorting
*  the DBF. Filtered TOP/BOTTOM/SKIP and GO/GOTO endpoints stream the cursor
*  and stop at the first visible row.
*
*  ORDERED SKIP
*  ------------
*  Ordered SKIP now does a single recno-precise cursor step: seek the current
*  (key,recno) in the LMDB index and MDB_NEXT/MDB_PREV. No position map, no DBF
*  scan -- O(log n) even on the FIRST skip. The old position-map cache remains
*  only as a fallback if the current record is not present in the index.
*
*  THE METRIC
*  ----------
*  SET TIMER ON makes the shell print elapsed per command. That is the proof:
*  every TOP / BOTTOM / GO TOP / GO BOTTOM / GOTO FIRST / GOTO LAST below
*  should now report in milliseconds regardless of the 5.5M row count.
*  Re-run against the OLD binary to capture the "before" numbers.
*
*  CORRECTNESS
*  -----------
*  TALK ON echoes the landing record number, and SMARTLIST reads a few rows
*  in logical order after each endpoint so the fast answer is also the RIGHT
*  answer (ordered TOP by SID must land on 50000000 Taylor Quinn).
*
*  RUN
*  ---
*  DOTSCRIPT TRACE scripts\pinocchio\pinocchio_nav_defect_proof.dts OUT tmp\pinocchio\nav_proof.log
* ============================================================
SET ECHO OFF
SET TIMER ON
SET TALK ON

SET PATH DBF DBF/pinocchio
SET PATH INDEXES INDEXES/pinocchio
SET PATH LMDB LMDB/pinocchio

* ============================================================
* SECTION A -- ENROLL (5.5M rows): the reported slow case
* ============================================================
ECHO === A0. open ENROLL + attach CDX, order by SID ===
SELECT 0
USE ENROLL
SET INDEX TO ENROLL
COUNT
SET ORDER TO TAG SID

ECHO === A1. TOP  (was minutes; expect milliseconds; canary SID 50000000) ===
TOP
SMARTLIST SID,CLS_ID NEXT 5

ECHO === A2. BOTTOM (reverse cursor, one step; expect milliseconds) ===
BOTTOM
SMARTLIST SID,CLS_ID NEXT 5

ECHO === A3. GO TOP / GO BOTTOM (endpoint via streaming cursor) ===
GO TOP
GO BOTTOM

ECHO === A4. GOTO FIRST / GOTO LAST (same endpoint primitives) ===
GOTO FIRST
GOTO LAST

ECHO === A5. repeated TOP x20 -- proves it is O(1), not a warmed cache ===
LOOP 20
  TOP
ENDLOOP

* ============================================================
* SECTION B -- ordered SKIP on ENROLL (LMDB-sourced, not DB scan)
* ============================================================
ECHO === B1. TOP then forward walk with SKIP ===
TOP
SKIP
SKIP
SKIP 10
SKIP 100

ECHO === B2. backward walk with SKIP ===
SKIP -1
SKIP -10

ECHO === B3. SKIP 0 re-reads current (no movement) ===
SKIP 0

* ============================================================
* SECTION C -- STUDENTS (1M rows): char-key endpoints (LNAME C20)
* ============================================================
ECHO === C0. open STUDENTS, order by SID (numeric key) ===
SELECT 1
USE STUDENTS
SET INDEX TO STUDENTS
COUNT
SET ORDER TO TAG SID
ECHO --- C1. TOP / BOTTOM by SID ---
TOP
BOTTOM

ECHO === C2. order by LNAME (char key) -- Anderson class should be first ===
SET ORDER TO TAG LNAME
TOP
SMARTLIST SID,LNAME,FNAME NEXT 10
BOTTOM
SMARTLIST SID,LNAME,FNAME NEXT 5

* ============================================================
* SECTION D -- descending endpoints (fix is ascending-aware)
* ------------------------------------------------------------
* DESCEND flips the active order direction. After it, TOP must return the
* record that was previously BOTTOM. If your build spells this differently,
* the runner reports "Unknown command" and continues -- adjust as needed.
* ============================================================
ECHO === D1. DESCEND then TOP/BOTTOM must swap ends ===
SELECT 0
SET ORDER TO TAG SID
DESCEND
TOP
SMARTLIST SID,CLS_ID NEXT 3
BOTTOM
SMARTLIST SID,CLS_ID NEXT 3
ASCEND

ECHO ============================================================
ECHO NAV PROOF COMPLETE. A zero exit code is NOT proof -- confirm:
ECHO   - every TOP/BOTTOM/GO/GOTO reports milliseconds (SET TIMER ON),
ECHO     NOT seconds/minutes, on the 5.5M ENROLL table
ECHO   - ordered TOP by SID lands on 50000000 Taylor Quinn (A1)
ECHO   - BOTTOM lands on the largest SID; endpoints agree across
ECHO     TOP / GO TOP / GOTO FIRST (and BOTTOM / GO BOTTOM / GOTO LAST)
ECHO   - SMARTLIST rows are in logical tag order at each endpoint
ECHO   - after DESCEND, TOP and BOTTOM swap (D1)
ECHO   - no "Unknown command", missing tag, or truncated-key errors
ECHO Compare these elapsed numbers against the pre-fix binary for the delta.
ECHO ============================================================
